Durban - Construction has begun at eThekwini Primary School in KwaMashu where 16 new classrooms and other facilities are being built to improve the lives of the pupils.
The Cotton On Foundation, the philanthropic arm of the Cotton On group, is funding and overseeing the school’s upgrade which includes the construction of new classrooms, ablution facilities, an admin block and a nutritional programme.

Cotton On Group South Africa country manager, Johan van Wyk, said the company does not measure itself by profit.
“We measure ourselves by the positive difference we can make in people’s lives. When I go to work, I think about every store that we open or every product that we sell that will create another opportunity for somebody to be fed or have a roof over their heads,” he said. 

“Quality education requires safe, equipped spaces for teaching, skilled and supported staff, good nutrition and programmes that empower learners”, said Tim Diamond, general manager of the Cotton On Foundation.AdChoicesADVERTISINGinRead invented by Teads
Principal of eThekwini Primary School, Gabisile Zulu, thanked the foundation.

“Indeed, our lives will never be the same. This is the best gift of all,” said Zulu.


 




Zulu said her pupils would be coming to school with enthusiasm, motivation and pride.AdChoicesADVERTISINGinRead invented by Teads
“This is, and will be, the pride of our community for generations to come,” she said.


 




The foundation connected with the school in 2015 through a Nelson Mandela Foundation partnership.

Lindo Mandela attended the event on behalf of the Nelson Mandela Foundation yesterday with her children Zazi and Ziwelene - who are the great grandchildren of Nelson Mandela.


 




Mandela thanked the teachers for their hard work.

 







